Problem #1

(a) Using the divusa data, fit a regression of with divorce as the response and unemployed, femlab, marriage, birth, and military as predictors. Compute the condition number and interpret its meaning.

library(faraway)
data(divusa)

lmod = lm(divorce ~ unemployed + femlab + marriage + birth + military, data = divusa)
summary(lmod)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = divorce ~ unemployed + femlab + marriage + birth + 
##     military, data = divusa)

## femlab       0.38365    0.03059  12.543  < 2e-16 ***

(b) For the same model, compute the VIFs. Is there evidence that collinearity causes some predictors not to be significant? Explain your answer.

require(faraway)
vif(x)
## unemployed     femlab   marriage      birth   military

inf = sqrt(vif(x))
inf
## unemployed     femlab   marriage      birth   military

print("There is not much variance inflation. We can interpret (inf) as telling us that the standard error is between 1.117853 and 1.900862 times larger than it would have been without collinearity.")

library(faraway)
data(prostate)

require(leaps)
## Loading required package: leaps
b <- regsubsets(lpsa ~ ., data = prostate)
rs <- summary(b)
rs$which
##   (Intercept) lcavol lweight   age  lbph   svi   lcp gleason pgg45
## 1        TRUE   TRUE   FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE   FALSE FALSE
## 2        TRUE   TRUE    TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE   FALSE FALSE
## 3        TRUE   TRUE    TRUE FALSE FALSE  TRUE FALSE   FALSE FALSE
## 4        TRUE   TRUE    TRUE FALSE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE   FALSE FALSE
## 5        TRUE   TRUE    TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE   FALSE FALSE
## 6        TRUE   TRUE    TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE   FALSE  TRUE
## 7        TRUE   TRUE    TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE   FALSE  TRUE
## 8        TRUE   TRUE    TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE    TRUE  TRUE
AIC <- 50*log(rs$rss/50) + (1:8)*2
plot(AIC ~ I(1:8), ylab="AIC", xlab="Number of Predictors")

plot(1:8,rs$adjr2,xlab="No. of Parameters",ylab="Adjusted R-square")

which.max(rs$adjr2)
## [1] 7
print("R^2 is the easiest method, as we can clerly see the removal of the highest point (7) corresponding to (gleason) yields the best results. This is also confirmed in the backward elimination method and AIC.")
## [1] "R^2 is the easiest method, as we can clerly see the removal of the highest point (7) corresponding to (gleason) yields the best results. This is also confirmed in the backward elimination method and AIC."

rs <- summary(b)
rs$which
##   (Intercept)   sex status income verbal
## 1        TRUE FALSE  FALSE   TRUE  FALSE
## 2        TRUE  TRUE  FALSE   TRUE  FALSE
## 3        TRUE  TRUE  FALSE   TRUE   TRUE
## 4        TRUE  TRUE   TRUE   TRUE   TRUE
AIC <- 50*log(rs$rss/50) + (1:5)*2
## Warning in 50 * log(rs$rss/50) + (1:5) * 2: longer object length is not a
## multiple of shorter object length
plot(AIC ~ I(1:5), ylab="AIC", xlab="Number of Predictors")

plot(1:4,rs$adjr2,xlab="No. of Parameters",ylab="Adjusted R-square")

which.max(rs$adjr2)
## [1] 3
print("Backward elimination method is the best method, as we can clerly see the removal of point (2) corresponding to (status) yields the best results. This is also confirmed somewhat confirmed in the rs-summary, though not with R^2")
